{{Infobox language | name = Ganza | nativename = غانزا | pronunciation = | states = [[Sudan]], [[Ethiopia]] | region = [[Asosa Zone]] of [[Benishangul-Gumuz Region]] | speakers = 3,000 | date = 2007 | ref = e18 | familycolor = Afro-Asiatic | fam2 = [[Omotic]] | fam3 = [[Mao languages|Mao]] | iso3 = gza | glotto = ganz1246 | glottorefname = Ganza }} '''Ganza''' (also Ganzo, Koma) (Arabic: غانزا) is an [[Omotic]] language spoken in [[Sudan]] and in the western [[Benishangul-Gumuz Region|Benishangul-Gumuz region]] of [[Ethiopia]], specifically in the village districts of Penishuba and Yabeldigis.
It also goes by the names Ganzo, Gwami, Koma, and Koma-Ganza.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ethnologue.com/language/gza|title=Ganza|newspaper=Ethnologue|access-date=2016-11-23}}</ref>
==Phonology==
{|class="wikitable" |+ Consonants |- ! colspan="2" rowspan="2" | ! colspan="2" |[[Bilabial consonant|Bilabial]] ! colspan="2" |[[Alveolar consonant|Alveolar]] ! rowspan="2" |[[Postalveolar consonant|Postalveolar]] ! rowspan="2" |[[Palatal consonant|Palatal]] ! colspan="2" |[[Velar consonant|Velar]] ! rowspan="2" |[[Glottal consonant|Glottal]] |- !<small>plain</small> !<small>[[Ejective consonant|ejective]]</small> !<small>plain</small> !<small>[[Ejective consonant|ejective]]</small> !<small>plain</small> !<small>[[Ejective consonant|ejective]]</small> |- align="center" ! colspan="2" |[[Nasal stop|Nasal]] |{{IPA link|m}} | |{{IPA link|n}} | | | |{{IPA link|ŋ}} | |{{IPA |ʔ̃}} |- align="center" ! rowspan="2" |[[Plosive consonant|Plosive]] !<small>voiceless</small> |{{IPA link|p}} |{{IPA link|pʼ}} |{{IPA link|t}} |{{IPA link|tʼ}} | | |{{IPA link|k}} |{{IPA link|kʼ}} |{{IPA link|ʔ}} |- align="center" !<small>voiced</small> |{{IPA link|b}} | |{{IPA link|d}} | | | |{{IPA link|ɡ}} | | |- align=center ! rowspan="2" |[[Fricative consonant|Fricative]] !<small>voiceless</small> | | |{{IPA link|s}} |{{IPA link|sʼ}} |{{IPA link|ʃ}} | | | |{{IPA link|h}} |- align=center !<small>voiced</small> | | |{{IPA link|z}} | | | | | | |- align="center" ! colspan="2" |[[Approximant consonant|Approximant]] | | |{{IPA link|l}} | | |{{IPA link|j}} |{{IPA link|w}} | | |- align="center" ! colspan="2" |[[Trill consonant|Trill]] | | |{{IPA link|r}} | | | | | | |}
Ganza does not utilize consonant length phonemically.<ref name="Smolders-2016">{{cite journal|last=Smolders|first=Joshua|date=2016|title=A Phonology of Ganza|url=http://journals.dartmouth.edu/cgi-bin/WebObjects/Journals.woa/1/xmlpage/1/document/1070|format=pdf|journal=Linguistic Discovery|volume=14|issue=1|pages=86–144|doi=10.1349/PS1.1537-0852.A.470|access-date=2017-01-16}}</ref>{{rp|106}}
{|class="wikitable" style="text-align: center;" |+ '''Vowels'''<ref name="Smolders-2016"/>{{rp|107}} |- ! ! [[Front vowel|Front]] !! [[Back vowel|Back]] |- ! [[Close vowel|Close]] | {{IPA link|i}} || {{IPA link|u}} |- ![[Close-mid vowel|Mid]] | {{IPA link|e}} || {{IPA link|o}} |- ![[Open vowel|Open]] |colspan="2"| {{IPA link|ä|a}} |}
Although [[vowel length]] is typically contrastive in [[Omotic languages]], Ganza does not have a clear contrast between long and short vowel phonemes. Instead, Ganza has predictable utterance-final vowel lengthening and a set of monosyllabic words with double vowels.<ref name="Smolders-2016"/>{{rp|109}}
