{{lowercase title}} {{Infobox non-profit | name = noyb | image = NOYB logo.png | type = [[non-profit organization]] | founded_date = {{Start date|2017|06|12}} | tax_id = 1354838270 | founder = | location = [[Vienna]], [[Austria]] | coordinates = | origins = | key_people = [[Max Schrems]], Petra Leupold, Christof Tschohl | area_served = | product = | mission = | focus = | method = | revenue = | endowment = | num_volunteers = | num_employees = | num_members = | subsid = | opponents = | owner = | non-profit_slogan = | former name = | homepage ={{URL|https://noyb.eu}} | dissolved = | footnotes = }} '''noyb.eu''', also called '''noyb''' (from the colloquial "none of your business") or '''NOYB – European Center for Digital Rights''', is a [[non-profit organization]] based in [[Vienna]], [[Austria]] established in 2017. Founded by Austrian lawyer and privacy activist [[Max Schrems]], noyb.eu aims to launch strategic court cases and media initiatives in support of the [[General Data Protection Regulation]], the proposed [[EPrivacy Regulation (European Union)|ePrivacy Regulation]], and information privacy in general.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.apnews.com/18a537b8b234445fa4eab2633a4a516d |title= Austrian activist launches consumers’ digital rights group |work=[[Associated Press]] |date=November 28, 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171211012810/https://www.apnews.com/18a537b8b234445fa4eab2633a4a516d |archivedate=December 10, 2017 |accessdate=December 10, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= Scally |first=Derek |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/technology/time-to-tell-tech-firms-that-private-data-is-none-of-your-business-max-schrems-1.3309734 |title=Time to tell tech firms that private data is ‘none of your business’ – Max Schrems |work=[[The Irish Times]] |date=November 30, 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171130082725/https://www.irishtimes.com/business/technology/time-to-tell-tech-firms-that-private-data-is-none-of-your-business-max-schrems-1.3309734 |archivedate=November 30, 2017 |accessdate=December 10, 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Hill |first=Rebecca |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2017/11/29/schrems_launches_privacy_enforcement_ngo_pulls_in_nearly_60k_in_first_24_hours/ |title=Max Schrems launches privacy NGO, wins €60k within first 24 hours |work=[[The Register]] |date=November 29, 2017 |deadurl=no |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171129225011/https://www.theregister.co.uk/2017/11/29/schrems_launches_privacy_enforcement_ngo_pulls_in_nearly_60k_in_first_24_hours/ |archivedate=November 29, 2017 |accessdate=December 10, 2017 }}</ref> While many privacy organizations focus attention on governments, noyb.eu puts its focus on privacy issues and privacy violations in the private sector.
Soon after [[General Data Protection Regulation]] rules went into effect on 25 May 2018, noyb filed complaints against Facebook and subsidiaries [[WhatsApp]] and [[Instagram]], as well as [[Google LLC]] (targeting [[Android (operating system)|Android]]), for allegedly violating Article 7(4) by attempting to completely block use of their services if users decline to accept all data processing consents, in a bundled grant which also includes consents deemed unnecessary to use the service.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://noyb.eu/wp-content/uploads/2018/05/pa_forcedconsent_en.pdf|title=GDPR: noyb.eu filed four complaints over "forced consent" against Google, Instagram, WhatsApp and Facebook|date=25 May 2018|publisher=NOYB.eu|dead-url=|access-date=26 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/5/25/17393766/facebook-google-gdpr-lawsuit-max-schrems-europe|title=Facebook and Google hit with $8.8 billion in lawsuits on day one of GDPR|work=The Verge|access-date=26 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/business/technology/max-schrems-files-first-cases-under-gdpr-against-facebook-and-google-1.3508177|title=Max Schrems files first cases under GDPR against Facebook and Google|work=The Irish Times|access-date=26 May 2018|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/05/25/facebook-google-face-first-gdpr-complaints-over-forced-consent/|title=Facebook, Google face first GDPR complaints over ‘forced consent’|website=TechCrunch|access-date=26 May 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/google-facebook-hit-with-serious-gdpr-complaints-others-will-be-soon/|title=Google, Facebook hit with serious GDPR complaints: Others will be soon|last=Meyer|first=David|publisher=ZDNet|access-date=26 May 2018|language=en}}</ref>
