The '''Timočani''' (also '''Timochani''', or '''Timochans''') ([[Serbian language|Serbian]] and [[Bulgarian language|Bulgarian]]: Тимочани) were a medieval [[South Slavs|South Slavic]] tribe that lived in the territory of present-day eastern [[Serbia]], west of the [[Timok River]], as well as in the regions of [[Banat]], [[Syrmia]] and [[Moesia Superior]].{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}}

Timočani settled in the Balkans in the 6th century and became later subjects of the [[Avar Khaganate]]. In 805 that area was conquered of the [[Bulgar Khanate]] under Khan [[Krum of Bulgaria|Krum]]. In 818 during the rule of [[Omurtag of Bulgaria]] (814-836) they, together with other border tribes of the First Bulgarian Empire, revolted because of an administrative reform that deprived them of much of their local authority.<ref>https://books.google.com/books?id=pi0xAAAAIAAJ</ref>

They, together with other Slavic tribes, searched protection from [[Holy Roman Emperor]] [[Louis the Pious]] in the same year, meeting him at his court at [[Herstal]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://historyexam.hit.bg/2.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-07-24 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100724014801/http://historyexam.hit.bg/2.htm |archivedate=2010-07-24 |df= }}</ref> Omurtag decided to settle the matter by means of diplomacy in 824-826, though his letters were not replied to by Louis. This prompted Omurtag to undertake a boat campaign on the [[Drava]] in 827 and invade the lands of the Timočani at [[Sirmium]], successfully imposing Bulgar rule again and appointing local governors. Many Timochans fled to Transdanubia, later becoming part of the [[Balaton Principality]].

Today, ''Timočani'' can be used as an informal name for the inhabitants of the [[Timok (river)|Timok]] region in Serbia and Bulgaria.<ref name=Stc>https://books.google.com/books?id=gXMtAQAAIAAJ</ref>

